f Robert Barnes and his reformation significance the author provides a comprehensive survey of the reformer's stormy career, a clear and convincing analysis of his often misconstrued theology, and a persuasive argument that the influence of Barnes and his novel polemical programme extended not only into the century following his death, but was as prominent on the continent as it was in his native England. KOREY MAAS is Associate Professor of Church History, Concordia University, Irvine, California  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian martyrszEnglandvBiography. 0aReformationzEngland. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aHistory of Religion. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aHenrician England.  aPapacy.  aPolemic.  aReformation.  aRobert Barnes.  aTheology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615807040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846158070423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846158070/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles